posts.cooked: we had the exact same thing happening last meeting, when we set all variables to 0 it still was running. What seems to be happening if that feedforward is being used even though the f term is 0. (we manually set the motor feedforward to all 0s with the PID loop being all 0s as well and that got the closed loop control to stop functioning) the feedforward seems to be doing the heavy lifting of the control loop. with the PID loop being used for fine tuning. if you are having an issue where your drive motors are significantly under-performing be sure to update yagsl

posts.name: Paul Rensing
posts.cooked:
We seem to be having the same problem, in that tuning the PID for the Drive does not help.

Digging through the code, the Feedforward term is not controlled by the “f” parameter in the JSON files (in fact see Bug in TalonFX PIDF · Issue #299 · BroncBotz3481/YAGSL-Example · GitHub ). It is controlled by a class in the SwerveModules themselves. The values are set from the max voltage, speed and wheel grip, at this code: YAGSL/swervelib/SwerveModule.java at main · BroncBotz3481/YAGSL · GitHub

It looks like the way to go is either turn down some of the parameters, or just override the FF class using SwerveDrive::replaceSwerveModuleFeedforward

We have not tested this yet, though.
